{{dynamic list}} This page serves as a timeline to show when analog devices were first made with digital circuits and systems.
*'''1642''': [[Blaise Pascal]] invents the [[mechanical calculator]].<ref>[[#DOCAGNE|Maurice d'Ocagne]] p.245 (1893)</ref><ref name=inventor>[[#MARG|Jean Marguin]], p. 48 (1994) ; Quoting [[#TATON63|René Taton]] (1963)</ref> This calculator could work in base 6, 10, 12 and 20. *'''1820''': [[Thomas de Colmar]] invents the [[arithmometer]]. Its production release in 1851 marks the beginning of the mechanical calculator industry.<ref>[[#CHASE|C. G. Chase]], page 204 (1980)</ref> *'''1822''': [[Difference engine]]: First mechanical computer created by [[Charles Babbage]]. *'''1837''': [[Analytical engine]]: Mechanical general-purpose computer created by [[Charles Babbage]]. *'''1843''': [[fax machine]]: a scanning, rasterized, digital replacement for the vectorized, analog [[telautograph]].[http://www.secretlifeofmachines.com/secret_life_of_the_fax_machine.shtml "The Secret Life of the Fax Machine"] by Tim Hunkin *'''1847''' (?) : [[piano roll]]: a digital recording of which notes were played. *'''1877''': [[gramophone record]]: an analog recording that more-or-less replaces the digital piano roll. *'''1921''': [[Edith Clarke]] patents the "Clarke calculator", a [[graphical calculator]] for simplifying calculations of inductance and capacity for electrical transmission lines.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lott|first1=Melissa C.|title=The Engineer Who Foreshadowed the Smart Grid--in 1921|url=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/plugged-in/the-engineer-who-foreshadowed-the-smart-grid-in-1921/|website=Plugged In|publisher=Scientific American Blog Network|accessdate=14 August 2017|language=en}}</ref> *'''1920s''', [[Bell Labs]] designed the first [[digital speakers|digital speaker]]. The product was abandoned before its release due to cost, size, unreliability, and overall impracticality. Even though many analog speakers have labels that say "digital", digital speakers today remain unavailable commercially.[[Digital speakers]] *'''1940'''(?) bookkeeping using [[Credit card#History|Charga-Plates]] to imprint account numbers, rather than writing them by hand. *'''1941''', [[Computer]]: [[Konrad Zuse]] develops the first digital computer, the [[Z3 (computer)]] *'''17 November 1947''', [[Transistor]]: [[John Bardeen]], [[Walter Brattain]], and [[William Shockley|Bill Shockley]] at [[AT&T Bell Labs]] made the first transistor. *'''1951''', [[Audio recording]]: Geoff Hill plays back the first [[digital audio]] recording of [[Colonel Bogey's March]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.indiana.edu/~emusic/etext/digital_audio/chapter5_digital.shtml |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161128105852/https://www.indiana.edu/~emusic/etext/digital_audio/chapter5_digital.shtml |archive-date=2016-11-28 |title=Digital Audio |work=Introduction to Computer Music}}</ref> *'''1954''', [[digital voltmeter]] replaces analog [[galvanometer]]. *'''1970''', [[Watch]]: [[Pulsar (watch)]] helped [[Hamilton Watch Company]] make real the prototype for the [[digital watch]] that Hamilton Watch Co. designed for the 1968 film ''[[2001: A Space Odyssey (film)|2001: A Space Odyssey]]''. The watch was completed in 1972 and sold for $2,100 USD.[[Watch#Digital]] *'''1973''', [[Telecommunication|Telephone service]]: The first [[VoIP|digital phone message]] was relayed over the [[ARPANET]] system.[https://web.archive.org/web/20090125122045/http://www.utdallas.edu/~bjackson/history.html] *'''December 1975''', [[Still image]]: [[Kodak]] engineer [[Steven Sasson]] creates the first [[digital camera]], weighing eight pounds and saving images to a cassette tape. Exposure time was 23 seconds. [[Digital camera#Early development]] *'''1979''' (?), [[Compact Disc]] *'''1982''', [[Video recording]]: The first [[digital video]] technology was made available.[https://web.archive.org/web/20081229155957/http://www.cytechandprofservices.com/vhistory.htm] *'''March 1, 1997''', [[Player Piano]]: [[QRS]] and [[Baldwin Piano Company|Baldwin]] collaborate to produce the first [[MIDI]]-compatible player piano.[https://web.archive.org/web/20080115221103/http://www.qrsmusic.com/press_details.asp?rid=12] *'''February 13, 1998''', [[Player Violin]]: [[QRS]] patents the first [[MIDI]]-compatible player violin.[http://www.qrsmusic.com/press_details.asp?rid=19] *'''October 1, 1998''', [[Television]]: [[British Sky Broadcasting]] launches the first [[digital television]] network. [[British Sky Broadcasting#Move to Digital]] *'''January 31, 2005''', [[Credit card]]: [[Fujitsu]] patents the Wireless Wallet, a cell phone that doubles as an electronic credit card for more secure transactions.[https://web.archive.org/web/20110612200604/http://www.patentstorm.us/applications/20050187873/fulltext.html]
